==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Crumple
<hw>Crum"ple</hw> <pr>(kr⟦ucr⟧m"p'l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Crumpled</conjf>
<pr>(-p'ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Crumpling</conjf>
<pr>(-pl⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Dim. fr. <ets>crump</ets>,
<ets>a.</ets>]</ety> <def>To draw or press into wrinkles or folds; to
crush together; to rumple; <as>as, to <ex>crumple</ex>
paper</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>crumpled</qex> it into all shapes, and diligently
scanned every wrinkle that could be made.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Crumple</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Crumple
<hw>Crum"ple</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To contract irregularly; to
show wrinkles after being crushed together; <as>as, leaves
<ex>crumple</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Crumpy</ent>⟦br⟧
